            <h2>The Quintessence of Programming</h2>

<p>In my short piece about using Tesseract's OCR engine in the command line, I described the <code>for</code> loop as the "quintessence of computer automation". Being a humble beginner programmer I should have known better than to make such a grandiose pronouncement. I defer to Dijkstra's vision of the quintessentialâ€” the variable as the fundamental building block of programming:</p>

<blockquote>
  <p>...that once a person has understood the way in which variables are used in programming, he has understood the quintessence of programming</p>
</blockquote>

<p>He explains that repetition creates this need to account for the multiple values that a variable can take on. The concept of a variable allows us to consider a quantity which takes on different values. It is the ability to deliver superhuman repetition which distinguishes the automatic computer.</p>

<h2>Humble Programming</h2>

<p>EWD's Turing Award lecture is entitled <em>The Humble Programmer</em>. The concluding paragraph ends with this appeal to humility:</p>

<blockquote>
  <p>We shall do a much better programming job, provided that we approach the task with a full appreciation of its tremendous difficulty, provided that we stick to modest and elegant programming languages, provided that we respect the intrinsic limitations of the human mind and approach the task as Very Humble Programmers.</p>
</blockquote>

<p>It's easy to be humble when your knowledge of a field is asymptotic to zero. But the beginner must use whatever tools she has accumulated in her life experience to advance. Many important matters boil down to aesthetic taste and one is pulled towards certain writings out of sheer horse sense. Dijkstra's clarity of thought and outspoken tone are a tonic to even the novice reader.</p>

